******
[2] Cote d'Ivoire
Date: Mon 23 Aug 2021
Date: Fri 20 Aug 2021
Source: Nairametrics [edited]
https://nairametrics.com/2021/08/20/guinea-identifies-58-contacts-of-ebola-patient-in-ivory-coast/


Guinean authorities have confirmed that 58 people have been confined to their homes after being identified as contacts of a woman who contracted the Ebola virus.

The Ebola case was discovered in Cote d'Ivoire in an 18-year-old Guinean woman who had travelled by bus from Labe, Guinea, a journey of some 1500 km (930 miles). It was Cote d'Ivoire's 1st known case of the disease since 1994.

Ebola is often deadly, causing severe fever and, in the worst cases, unstoppable bleeding. It is transmitted through close contact with bodily fluids, and people who live with or care for patients are most at risk.

The discovery in Cote d'Ivoire came nearly 2 months after the United Nations' health agency declared an end to Guinea's 2nd Ebola outbreak, which started last year [2020] and killed 12 people.

Regional health director, Elhadj Mamadou Houdy Bah told the AFP news agency, "In Labe, 58 contacts have been identified. However, the good news is that none of them are presenting any signs (of Ebola) at the moment, all are being followed."

The driver of the vehicle that transported the young Ebola sufferer to Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, is one of those identified.

As the sole centre in Labe able to handle such contact cases is currently full dealing with coronavirus patients, the Ebola contact cases were placed under confinement at home for an observation period of 21 days, the Guinean health authorities said.

An Ebola outbreak between 2013 and 2016 killed 11 300 people throughout West Africa, including 2300 people in Guinea. Meanwhile, the World Health Organization (WHO) believes the toll has been underestimated.

On Tuesday [17 Aug 2021], the WHO said 9 Ebola contact cases had been identified in Cote d'Ivoire, following the case of the Guinean woman who is currently being treated in a hospital in Abidjan, while health workers are being vaccinated against the disease.

[Byline: Chidinma Anyalewechi]

